{"schema_version": 2, "source_hash": "7807a701262ad567", "candidate": {"id": "cand-021", "name": "James Fletcher", "raw_cv": "JAMES FLETCHER\njames.fletcher@email.com | London, UK\n\nSENIOR SOFTWARE ENGINEER\n\nPROFESSIONAL SUMMARY\nBackend software engineer with 7 years of experience building high-throughput payment and financial services APIs. Deep expertise in Python and Go, with a strong focus on distributed systems and service reliability. Experienced in regulated environments with PCI-DSS and FCA compliance requirements.\n\nEXPERIENCE\n\nSenior Software Engineer \u2014 Checkout.com, London (2021\u2013present)\n- Own the payment authorisation service processing 8,000 TPS at peak, written in Go\n- Led a re-architecture from monolith to event-driven microservices using Kafka and gRPC\n- Introduced structured observability (OpenTelemetry + Datadog) across 6 backend services\n- Mentored 3 junior engineers; conducted system design interviews\n\nSoftware Engineer \u2014 Monzo Bank, London (2019\u20132021)\n- Built core banking API features in Python (Flask \u2192 FastAPI migration)\n- Delivered the overdraft eligibility engine, integrating with 4 external credit bureaus\n- Contributed to the internal service mesh migration (Consul \u2192 Linkerd)\n\nJunior Software Engineer \u2014 ThoughtWorks, London (2017\u20132019)\n- Delivered backend features for enterprise clients in Java and Python\n- Certified AWS Developer (2018)\n\nSKILLS\nGo, Python, Java, gRPC, Kafka, PostgreSQL, Redis, Docker, Kubernetes, Terraform, Datadog, OpenTelemetry, Git\n\nEDUCATION\nBEng Software Engineering \u2014 University of Bristol (2014\u20132017)\n\nRIGHT TO WORK\nBritish citizen", "raw_linkedin": "Backend engineer with seven years in payments and fintech. I build the services that move money \u2014 currently at Checkout.com where I own the authorisation platform. I've spent my career optimising for correctness and reliability at scale, which in payments means they're the same thing. I'm most comfortable in Go and Python, with a strong bias towards observable, well-tested systems. I enjoy mentoring and I've been doing a lot of system design coaching lately. Looking for senior or staff-level backend roles in fintech, payments, or infrastructure-heavy product companies. London-based, open to hybrid.", "raw_interview_transcript": "Interviewer: Thanks for coming in, James. Tell me about the authorisation service you own at Checkout.\n\nJames: The authorisation service is the critical path for every card transaction \u2014 it sits between the merchant and the card networks. At peak we're doing around 8,000 transactions per second. It's written in Go, which I championed because the latency profile is much more predictable than Python at that scale. One of the bigger pieces of work I've led is moving from a synchronous request-response model to an event-driven architecture using Kafka, which lets us handle traffic spikes much more gracefully.\n\nInterviewer: How do you think about reliability and observability?\n\nJames: I think observability is a first-class concern, not an afterthought. When I joined, the services had basic Prometheus metrics but no traces and inconsistent logging. I introduced OpenTelemetry across our six core services and wired everything into Datadog. Now when something goes wrong at 2am, the on-call engineer has enough context to diagnose in minutes rather than hours.\n\nInterviewer: What are you looking for in your next role?\n\nJames: I want to go deeper on the architecture side \u2014 ideally taking on a staff or tech lead role where I'm owning technical direction across a domain rather than just a single service. I'm also keen to work somewhere where engineering quality genuinely matters to the business, not just the engineering team.\n\nInterviewer: This role is 3 days in the office, 2 remote. Any issues there?\n\nJames: That works well. I live in Bermondsey so central London offices are very easy for me.\n\nInterviewer: Salary expectations?\n\nJames: I'm at \u00a398,000 at Checkout. I'm looking for \u00a3105\u2013115,000 for this move.", "years_experience": 7.0, "skills": ["Go", "Python", "Java", "gRPC", "Kafka", "PostgreSQL", "Redis", "Docker", "Kubernetes", "Terraform", "Datadog", "OpenTelemetry", "Git", "system design", "mentoring", "backend API development", "microservices architecture", "distributed systems", "event-driven architecture"], "industries": ["payments", "fintech", "financial services", "banking"], "seniority_level": "senior", "management_experience": true, "education_level": "bachelor", "career_trajectory": "ascending", "interview_score": 0.88, "culture_fit_score": 0.85, "constraints": [{"id": "d2297e43", "type": "hard", "side": "candidate", "category": "compensation", "description": "Current salary at Checkout.com is \u00a398,000 (from interview)", "canonical_key": "salary_current", "value": 98000.0, "operator": "requires", "weight": 0.9, "confidence": 0.98, "currency": "GBP"}, {"id": "ff3ce238", "type": "hard", "side": "candidate", "category": "compensation", "description": "Seeking minimum salary of \u00a3105,000 for next role", "canonical_key": "salary_min", "value": 105000.0, "operator": "min", "weight": 0.95, "confidence": 0.95, "currency": "GBP"}, {"id": "2b33d298", "type": "soft", "side": "candidate", "category": "compensation", "description": "Target salary range \u00a3105\u2013115,000 for next opportunity", "canonical_key": "salary_target", "value": 115000.0, "operator": "prefers", "weight": 0.85, "confidence": 0.92, "currency": "GBP"}, {"id": "86514afb", "type": "hard", "side": "candidate", "category": "location", "description": "Comfortable with 3 days office, 2 remote arrangement (interview)", "canonical_key": "office_days_per_week", "value": 3.0, "operator": "prefers", "weight": 0.8, "confidence": 0.85, "currency": null}, {"id": "d2a8a3db", "type": "soft", "side": "candidate", "category": "location", "description": "London-based, Bermondsey resident; central 